First, we need to translate the sentence into Swedish: "Nackdelen är att tekniken att bygga med stålreglar ofta är ny för hantverkare och därmed kräver mer tid."

Here is the dependency tree:

[(1, Nackdelen, 3), (2, är, 3), (3, är, 0), (4, att, 5), (5, tekniken, 4), (6, att, 7), (7, bygga, 6), (8, med, 9), (9, stålreglar, 7), (10, ofta, 11), (11, är, 11), (12, ny, 11), (13, för, 12), (14, hantverkare, 13), (15, och, 17), (16, därmed, 17), (17, kräver, 6), (18, mer, 19), (19, tid, 17)]

Explanation:
- 'Nackdelen' is a noun and has a dependency on the linking verb 'är' (index 3)
- 'är' (index 2) is also dependent on 'är' (index 3) for its role in the sentence structure.
- 'är' (index 3) is the main verb and the head of the sentence (dependency is 0).
- 'tekniken' (index 5) is the subject of the embedded clause and has a dependency on the preposition 'att' (index 4) which in turn is dependent on 'är' (index 3)
- 'bygga' (index 7) is the main verb of the embedded clause and 'att' (index 6) is the head of the verb phrase including 'bygga' and the prepositional phrase that follows
- 'med' (index 8), 'stålreglar' (index 9), 'ofta' (index 10), 'är' (index 11), 'ny' (index 12), 'för' (index 13) and 'hantverkare' (index 14) all relate to each other and to 'bygga' (index 7) as 'bygga' is the verb of the embedded clause
- The adverb 'därmed' (index 16) and the coordinating conjunction 'och' (index 15) are both used to connect 'kräver' (index 17) to the rest of the sentence.

The final time required is shown with 'mer' (index 18) as the adverb and 'tid' (index 19) as the noun acting as the object.